SIMPLE: space
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Space
<hw>Space</hw> <pr>(sp⟦amac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>space</ets>, F. <ets>espace</ets>, from L. <ets>spatium</ets>
space; cf. Gr. <grk>spa^n</grk> to draw, to tear; perh. akin to E.
<ets>span</ets>. Cf. <er>Expatiate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Extension, considered independently of anything which it may
contain; that which makes extended objects conceivable and
possible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pure <qex>space</qex> is capable neither of resistance nor
motion.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Place, having more or less extension;
room.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They gave him chase, and hunted him as hare;⟦br⟧
Long had he no <qex>space</qex> to dwell [in].</q> <rj><qau>R. of
Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While I have time and <qex>space</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A quantity or portion of extension; distance from
one thing to another; an interval between any two or more objects;
<as>as, the <ex>space</ex> between two stars or two hills; the sound was
heard for the <ex>space</ex> of a mile</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Put a <qex>space</qex> betwixt drove and drove.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xxxii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Quantity of time; an interval between two points of
time; duration; time.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Grace God gave him here, this land to
keep long <xex>space</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>R. of brunne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nine times the <qex>space</qex> that measures day and night.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God may defer his judgments for a time, and give a people a longer
<qex>space</qex> of repentance.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A short time; a while.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧To stay your deadly strife a <xex>space</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Walk; track; path; course.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This ilke [same] monk let old things pace,⟦br⟧
And held after the new world the <qex>space</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small piece of
metal cast lower than a face type, so as not to receive the ink in
printing, -- used to separate words or letters.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The distance or interval between words or letters in the lines, or
between lines, as in books, on a computer screen, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Spaces are of different thicknesses to enable the
compositor to arrange the words at equal distances from each other in
the same line.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>One of the intervals, or open
places, between the lines of the staff.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>that portion of the universe outside the earth or
its atmosphere; -- called also <altname>outer space</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Absolute space</b></col>, <col><b>Euclidian
space</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Absolute</er>,
<er>Euclidian</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>deep space</b></col>, <cd>the
part of outer space which is beyond the limits of the solar system.</cd>
-- <col><b>Space line</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>a thin piece of
metal used by printers to open the lines of type to a regular distance
from each other, and for other purposes; a lead.</cd> <au>Hansard.</au>
-- <col><b>Space rule</b></col> <fld>(Print.)</fld>, <cd>a fine, thin,
short metal rule of the same height as the type, used in printing short
lines in tabular matter.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Space</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Space
<hw>Space</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>espacier</ets>, L.
<ets>spatiari</ets>. See <er>Space</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To
walk; to rove; to roam.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And loved in forests wild to <qex>space</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Space</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Space
<hw>Space</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spaced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spacong</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>espacer</ets>. See <er>Space</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>To arrange or adjust the spaces in or between;
<as>as, to <ex>space</ex> words, lines, or letters</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Space age</ent>⟦br⟧
